<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Puducherry</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Where <em>France Meets India</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Puducherry — formerly Pondicherry, still called Pondy with great affection — is the most unexpected place in India: a former French colonial enclave on the Coromandel Coast of the Bay of Bengal that retained its French character so completely that walking through the Ville Blanche (White Town) today feels like stepping into a Mediterranean coastal village — yellow and ochre walls draped in bougainvillea, shuttered French colonial villas lining streets with French names (Rue de la Marine, Rue Dumas, Rue Romain Rolland), a beachside promenade with a French war memorial, gendarmerie (police) in red-and-black kepis and a French consulate still operating on the Rue de la Caserne. The French ruled Pondicherry from 1674 to 1954 — 280 years of occupation that left behind not just architecture but a creole culture, a Franco-Tamil cuisine, a French-medium school system and a community of Franco-Pondichérien families who hold dual French-Indian citizenship and whose grandparents spoke French at home. Puducherry is also the home of Sri Aurobindo Ashram — the spiritual centre established by Sri Aurobindo Ghosh (a Bengali revolutionary turned mystic) and the Mother (Mirra Alfassa, a French-Egyptian woman) in 1926 that has attracted spiritual seekers from every continent for nearly a century. 14 kilometres north of Puducherry, Auroville — the extraordinary intentional community founded in 1968 with a vision of human unity beyond nationality, religion and politics — hosts 3,000 residents from 60 nations around the golden Matrimandir meditation sphere. Puducherry's four districts are geographically separated from each other — Puducherry district on the Tamil Nadu coast, Karaikal further south on the coast, and Mahe and Yanam as tiny enclaves hundreds of kilometres away in Kerala and Andhra Pradesh respectively — a legacy of the fragmentary nature of French colonial acquisition in India.</p>
</section>

