const placesData=[
  {emoji:"🏘️",name:"Ville Blanche — French Quarter",location:"Central Puducherry",desc:"The most evocative neighbourhood in India — the Ville Blanche (White Town) is a 2-square-kilometre grid of French colonial streets where yellow and ochre plaster villas are draped in bougainvillea, shuttered windows open onto tree-lined streets with French names, and policemen (formerly gendarmerie) still wear red-and-black kepis. The streets Rue de la Marine, Rue Dumas, Rue Romain Rolland and Rue Suffren form the core of an area that has been maintained largely intact since French rule ended in 1954. The best time: early morning, when the light is golden and the streets are quiet.",fee:["Free — open neighbourhood"]},
  {emoji:"🙏",name:"Sri Aurobindo Ashram",location:"Rue de la Marine, Puducherry",desc:"Founded in 1926 by Sri Aurobindo Ghosh — Bengali revolutionary turned philosopher-mystic — and Mirra Alfassa (The Mother, a French-Egyptian woman), the Sri Aurobindo Ashram has become one of India's most significant spiritual centres. The Samadhi (tomb) of Sri Aurobindo and The Mother in the ashram's inner courtyard is covered daily with fresh flowers by thousands of visitors in an atmosphere of profound stillness. The ashram's philosophy — Integral Yoga, the transformation of human consciousness — has attracted seekers from every continent. The ashram also runs schools, a press, farms, workshops and guesthouses.",fee:["Free — 8am to noon, 2pm to 6pm"]},
  {emoji:"🌍",name:"Auroville — City of Human Unity",location:"12km north of Puducherry",desc:"One of the world's most extraordinary experiments in human living — Auroville was founded on February 28, 1968, when representatives of 124 nations symbolically placed a handful of their native soil into a marble urn. The vision: a universal township where people of all nations, religions and backgrounds could live in harmony. Today 3,000 residents from 60 countries live in Auroville, growing their own food, running sustainable businesses, building innovative architecture and meditating in the Matrimandir — a golden geodesic sphere at the city's centre, containing a meditation chamber of extraordinary purity with a crystal globe illuminated by a solar ray.",fee:["Visitor Centre free","Matrimandir inner chamber — advance booking required"]},
  {emoji:"🌊",name:"Promenade Beach (Rock Beach)",location:"East Puducherry — Bay of Bengal",desc:"Puducherry's defining public space — the 4-kilometre promenade along the Bay of Bengal, with the French War Memorial, the statue of Dupleix (the great French Governor), the lighthouse and the town beach all aligned along a seafront boulevard lined with shade trees. At dawn, hundreds of locals gather on the rocks for yoga, prayer and conversation. At dusk, the promenade fills with families, vendors and cyclists. The sea here is rough and rocky — not a swimming beach — but one of India's finest urban seafronts, with the city's French architecture as the backdrop.",fee:["Free"]},
  {emoji:"⛪",name:"Basilica of the Sacred Heart of Jesus",location:"South Boulevard, Puducherry",desc:"The most spectacular church in Puducherry — the Basilica of the Sacred Heart of Jesus was built by the French missionaries in 1908 in a striking Gothic style with intricate stained glass windows depicting scenes from the life of Jesus, brought from France. The church is particularly beautiful at morning mass when the stained glass casts pools of coloured light across the congregation. Puducherry's Christian community — descendants of converts from the French colonial period — maintains the church with exceptional care.",fee:["Free — respectful dress required"]},
  {emoji:"🌿",name:"Botanical Garden",location:"Central Puducherry",desc:"Established in 1826 by the French — making it one of the oldest botanical gardens in South India — the Puducherry Botanical Garden contains over 1,500 plant species from around the world, with a particular emphasis on tropical and French colonial-era introductions. The garden has a French formal garden design at its centre (clipped hedges, symmetrical paths, fountain) surrounded by a more naturalistic tropical planting. The aquarium within the garden is small but displays the extraordinary marine life of the Bay of Bengal.",fee:["Rs.10 Indians","Rs.100 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🕌",name:"Manakula Vinayagar Temple",location:"Ville Blanche, Puducherry",desc:"The most visited temple in Puducherry — the Manakula Vinayagar Temple (dedicated to Ganesha) sat stubbornly in the heart of the French colonial quarter throughout 280 years of French rule, despite repeated French attempts to relocate it. Its survival is a symbol of Tamil religious identity's resistance to colonial erasure. The elephant of the temple — a trained elephant that blesses devotees with its trunk at the entrance — is one of Puducherry's most photographed subjects. The temple's gopuram (tower) is decorated with elaborate stucco figures.",fee:["Free"]},
  {emoji:"🚴",name:"Heritage Cycling Walk — White Town",location:"Puducherry French Quarter",desc:"The most satisfying way to experience Puducherry — cycling or walking the streets of the French Quarter at dawn. The Heritage Quarter Walk takes in the French consul's residence, the Lycée Français, the Alliance Française, the Institut Français de Pondichéry (a renowned research institute), the old French Hospital and dozens of privately owned villas whose owners maintain the yellow-ochre plaster as a condition of the heritage conservation rules. Heritage walks are conducted by the French Institute and local guides daily.",fee:["Free — guided walk fees apply"]},
];

const artsData=[
  {emoji:"🎨",name:"Auroville Architecture — Buildings of the Future",location:"Auroville, 12km north",desc:"Auroville has become one of the world's most significant laboratories of sustainable architecture and urban design — the community's buildings, designed over 50 years by architects from 30 countries, represent an extraordinary range of approaches to tropical construction, solar energy use, earth-building, bamboo architecture and community-centred design. The Matrimandir — a golden geodesic sphere designed by Roger Anger — is recognised internationally as one of the most significant spiritual buildings of the 20th century. The Auroville Earth Institute is now a global centre for compressed earth block construction."},
  {emoji:"🖼️",name:"French Colonial Architecture — Living Heritage",location:"Ville Blanche, Puducherry",desc:"The Ville Blanche is one of Asia's finest surviving examples of French colonial domestic architecture — the villas, churches, government buildings and commercial structures built between the 17th and 20th centuries create a coherent townscape of extraordinary quality. The Institut Français de Pondichéry conducts ongoing architectural documentation and conservation research. Several private individuals have meticulously restored their colonial villas, turning them into heritage hotels that allow visitors to experience the architecture from inside."},
  {emoji:"🎭",name:"Tamil Classical Arts & Bharatanatyam",location:"Tamil Quarter (Ville Noire), Puducherry",desc:"While the French Quarter gets most attention, Puducherry's Tamil Quarter (Ville Noire) is the living heart of Tamil classical culture — Bharatanatyam dance, Carnatic music, traditional Tamil festivals and temple arts are practiced with great vitality. The Tamil Quarter has its own cultural institutions: the Kalakshetra-affiliated dance schools, the Carnatic music sabhas and the elaborate temple festivals of the Manakula Vinayagar and other temples that proceed with no French influence whatsoever."},
  {emoji:"📚",name:"Sri Aurobindo's Philosophy & Literature",location:"Sri Aurobindo Ashram, Puducherry",desc:"Sri Aurobindo (1872-1950) was one of India's most prolific and profound writers — his Integral Yoga philosophy, expressed in works like The Life Divine, Savitri (a 24,000-line epic poem), The Synthesis of Yoga and Essays on the Gita, represents one of the great intellectual achievements of 20th century India. The Sri Aurobindo Ashram Press publishes his complete works (37 volumes) and the ashram's library maintains one of India's most significant collections of spiritual literature. His writings are studied worldwide."},
  {emoji:"🌸",name:"Puducherry's Café & Creative Culture",location:"Rue Suffren, Rue Dumas & throughout White Town",desc:"The café culture of Puducherry is unlike anywhere else in India — café-bakeries serving croissants, café au lait, crêpes and pain au chocolat alongside filter coffee and idli; bookshops with French and English literature; art galleries in restored colonial buildings; yoga studios; independent designers using traditional Tamil weaving and block printing with contemporary aesthetics. The streets of the White Town have become a creative district — boutique hotels, organic restaurants, handmade jewellery studios and organic farms collectively creating an atmosphere unlike any other Indian city."},
  {emoji:"🧘",name:"Yoga & Meditation Culture",location:"Auroville, Sri Aurobindo Ashram & throughout",desc:"Puducherry is one of India's most significant centres of yoga and meditation — the Sri Aurobindo Ashram's Integral Yoga tradition, Auroville's various meditation practices and the dozens of yoga retreat centres that have grown around the city create an atmosphere of spiritual inquiry unusually concentrated in a small urban area. The Iyengar Yoga tradition has particularly strong roots here. The morning yoga sessions on Promenade Beach — attended by local families, ashram residents and international visitors alike — are one of the most democratic spiritual rituals in India."},
