  {emoji:"🌺",name:"Pongal — Tamil Harvest Festival",location:"Tamil Quarter & throughout — January",desc:"Pongal — the four-day Tamil harvest festival (January 13-16) — is celebrated with extraordinary energy in Puducherry's Tamil quarter. The ritual boiling of new rice with milk and jaggery until it overflows the pot (symbolising abundance); the elaborate kolam (rice flour rangoli) drawn in front of every home; the Jallikattu bull-taming events in surrounding villages; and the community gathering at the Manakula Vinayagar Temple create a festival of profound Tamil cultural identity."},
  {emoji:"🕯️",name:"Masi Magam — Beach Festival",location:"Promenade Beach — February/March",desc:"One of Puducherry's most spectacular events — the Masi Magam festival (held on the full moon of the Tamil month Masi, usually February-March) sees temple deities from across Puducherry brought in procession to the beach to bathe in the sea. Thousands of devotees — many having walked miles — take a ritual dip in the Bay of Bengal at the same time as the deities. The sight of elaborately decorated temple chariots at the water's edge, the sound of nadaswaram and drums, and the crowds extending down the beach is extraordinary."},
  {emoji:"🙏",name:"Sri Aurobindo's Birthday — August 15",location:"Sri Aurobindo Ashram — August 15",desc:"Sri Aurobindo was born on August 15, 1872 — the same date as India's Independence Day, which Sri Aurobindo took as a divine sign of the country's spiritual destiny. The birthday celebration at the ashram on August 15 is a major spiritual event — devotees from across India and the world gather at the Samadhi, the ashram holds special meditations and programmes, and the entire Puducherry celebrates simultaneously as India's Independence Day. The convergence of the two occasions gives August 15 in Puducherry a unique spiritual-political resonance."},
